\begin{abstract}
\noindent
Cancer is one of the most complex diseases known to medicine, characterised by
the uncontrolled, invasive proliferation of malignant cells.  Classical oncology
models treat tumour growth as a deterministic, continuous process.  Here we
propose a fundamentally different perspective: that a tumour-infiltrated tissue
is a \emph{self-organised critical} (SOC) complex network, in which cancer cells
are nodes and intercellular signalling pathways are edges, and where malignant
conversion cascades (recruitment avalanches) are the primary dynamical events.
Using a Barab\'{a}si--Albert scale-free tissue network ($N = 300$ cells, mean
degree $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$) coupled with a stochastic mutation-accumulation
and threshold-recruitment model, we simulate tumour progression from a handful
of pre-cancerous seed cells to full network invasion.  Our model reproduces
four hallmarks of complex critical systems: (i) a power-law frequency
distribution of malignant-recruitment avalanches with exponent $\alpha \approx
0.99$, (ii) scale-free degree distribution of the tumour sub-network consistent
with preferential attachment, (iii) a sharp percolation-like phase transition
in cascade fraction as inter-cell connectivity $k$ crosses a critical threshold
$k_c \approx 4$, and (iv) persistent long-range correlations in tumour-growth
dynamics (Hurst exponent $H \approx 0.98 \gg 0.5$).  These results support the
hypothesis that tumour invasion is not a smooth, predictable process but an
intermittent, scale-free avalanche phenomenon driven by the tissue network
operating at or near a critical point.  The implications for early-warning
biomarkers, anti-cancer drug targeting, and network-based therapeutic
strategies are discussed.

\vspace{6pt}
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:}
Self-organised criticality, cancer network model, Barab\'{a}si--Albert graph,
tumour invasion, recruitment avalanche, percolation, power law, Hurst exponent,
complex systems, computational oncology.
\end{abstract}

