\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Motivation and Background}

Cancer kills approximately 10 million people annually worldwide, making it the
second-leading cause of death globally \citep{sung2021global}.  Despite
enormous investment in research and treatment, the fundamental dynamics of how
a tumour grows, evades the immune system, and invades surrounding tissue remain
incompletely understood.  Classical models --- from the Gompertz growth equation
to reaction-diffusion PDE models --- treat the tumour as a spatially smooth,
mechanistically deterministic object.  These models can reproduce average
growth curves, but they systematically fail to explain the \emph{heterogeneity}
of tumour growth: the sudden explosive phases of invasion, the long quiescent
periods, and the catastrophic metastatic transitions that define the natural
history of aggressive cancers.

Complexity science offers a radically different lens.  A tissue is not a
homogeneous medium --- it is a \emph{network} of $\sim 10^{10}$ interacting
cells connected by physical contacts, gap junctions, paracrine signalling
cascades, and extracellular matrix scaffolding.  When we adopt this network
perspective, the hallmarks of cancer described by \citet{hanahan2011hallmarks}
--- sustained proliferation, invasion, angiogenesis, immune evasion ---
can be reinterpreted as network-theoretic phenomena: hub nodes (stem cells,
super-spreader cells) driving preferential recruitment, percolation transitions
marking the onset of invasion, and avalanche dynamics governing the episodic
burst-and-quiescence pattern of growth.

The concept of \textbf{Self-Organised Criticality} (SOC), introduced by
\citet{bak1987self}, provides the unifying mathematical framework.  An SOC
system is one that spontaneously evolves toward a critical state --- a state
poised at the boundary between order and disorder --- without requiring external
tuning of any control parameter.  At this critical point, perturbations trigger
responses (avalanches) of all possible sizes, described by power-law statistics
with no characteristic scale.  The paradigmatic example is the sandpile: grains
added one at a time cause avalanches ranging from single-grain relaxations to
system-spanning collapses.

\textbf{Is a tumour an SOC system?}  We argue yes, for the following reasons:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Mutations accumulate slowly (the ``slow drive''), while malignant
        conversion and recruitment propagate rapidly through signalling networks
        (the ``fast relaxation'').
  \item Empirical studies of tumour heterogeneity reveal scale-free clone-size
        distributions \citep{sottoriva2015big}, consistent with SOC.
  \item Metastasis --- the catastrophic spread of cancer to distant sites ---
        has the hallmarks of a percolation transition: a sudden, system-spanning
        cascade that cannot be predicted from local observations alone.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Objectives of this Project}

This project addresses four research questions:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item Is a tissue/tumour network a good candidate for complexity-science
        analysis, and specifically for the SOC framework?
  \item Can a minimal network-based agent model reproduce the known statistical
        signatures of tumour growth (power laws, long-range correlations)?
  \item How does intercellular connectivity $k$ shape the ``avalanche'' dynamics
        of malignant recruitment?
  \item Does the simulated system exhibit spontaneous self-organisation toward a
        critical state?
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Scope and Novelty}

While several authors have applied complex-network ideas to cancer biology
\citep{barabasi2011network, hanahan2011hallmarks}, a unified treatment of
tumour invasion as a SOC phenomenon on a Barab\'{a}si--Albert tissue network,
with explicit avalanche statistics and percolation analysis, constitutes a
novel contribution at the intersection of computational oncology and
complexity science.

