\section{The Tumour as a Complex System}

\subsection{Why Cancer is a Good Candidate for SOC Analysis}

A system is a good candidate for SOC if it satisfies the following structural
criteria \citep{bak1996how, jensen1998self}:

\subsubsection{Many interacting agents with local rules}
A tissue contains billions of cells whose behaviour is governed by local
biochemical signals: growth factors, contact inhibition, gap-junction coupling,
cytokine gradients.  No single cell has global information about the tissue
state.  This is the defining characteristic of an agent-based complex system.

\subsubsection{Separation of timescales: slow drive, fast relaxation}
Oncogenic mutations accumulate over years to decades (the slow drive), while
a recruitment cascade --- once a threshold is crossed --- can propagate through
a local neighbourhood within hours via paracrine signalling (the fast
relaxation).  This separation is the essential prerequisite for SOC dynamics
\citep{bak1987self}.

\subsubsection{Threshold-triggered cascades}
When a cell's accumulated mutation load exceeds the Vogelstein multi-hit
threshold \citep{vogelstein2013cancer}, it undergoes malignant transformation
and begins secreting growth factors that lower the transformation threshold of
neighbouring cells.  This is mathematically identical to the toppling rule in
a sandpile or the threshold cascade in a financial network.

\subsubsection{Absence of characteristic scale}
Empirical measurements of clone-size distributions in human colon cancer
\citep{sottoriva2015big} and breast cancer \citep{yates2015subclonal} exhibit
power-law behaviour spanning many orders of magnitude --- a definitive signature
that the system has no characteristic scale and is operating near criticality.

\subsubsection{Scale-free network topology}
Protein--protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, and
intercellular signalling networks all exhibit scale-free degree distributions
$P(k) \sim k^{-\gamma}$ with $\gamma \approx 2$--$3$
\citep{barabasi1999emergence}, arising from preferential attachment (new
signalling connections preferentially form to already well-connected hub nodes,
e.g.\ oncoproteins such as TP53, MYC, EGFR).

\subsection{The Three Core Complexity Observables}

\subsubsection{Noise}
In the model, noise represents stochastic exogenous mutagens: UV radiation,
reactive oxygen species, replication errors, and random epigenetic alterations.
At each Monte-Carlo step, each healthy cell $i$ gains a mutation with
probability:
\begin{equation}
  p_{\text{mut}}(i,t) = \mu_0 + |\eta_i(t)|, \qquad
  \eta_i(t) \sim \mathcal{N}(0,\,\sigma^2),
\end{equation}
where $\mu_0 = 0.04$ is the base mutation rate and $\sigma = 0.02$ is the
standard deviation of stochastic noise (exogenous shocks: mutagen spikes,
radiation bursts).  The absolute value ensures noise only \emph{increases}
mutational load, consistent with the biological asymmetry: mutations
accumulate but are rarely precisely reversed.  The noise is small relative to
the conversion threshold, maintaining the slow-drive regime.

\subsubsection{Avalanche}
An avalanche (malignant recruitment cascade) is triggered when a cell's
mutation load $m_i \geq \theta = 5$ (the multi-hit threshold).  The cell
converts to cancerous and begins recruiting its healthy neighbours: each
healthy neighbour $j$ converts with probability $\rho = 0.25$ per contact
per step, propagating the cascade wave-front.  The \emph{avalanche size}
$s$ is the total number of cells that convert during a single cascade event.
Biologically, this represents the episodic explosive growth observed in
histopathological studies.  Open boundary conditions (cells with no
neighbours lose recruitment pressure) provide the dissipation channel that
prevents unlimited cascade growth and sustains the critical state.

\subsubsection{Connectivity}
Connectivity $k(t)$ is the mean degree of the tumour sub-network at time $t$:
\begin{equation}
  k(t) \;=\; \frac{1}{|C(t)|} \sum_{i \in C(t)} \deg_{\mathcal{G}}(i),
\end{equation}
where $C(t) = \{i : \text{state}(i) = \text{CANCEROUS}\}$ is the set of
cancerous cells and $\mathcal{G}$ is the tissue network.  High connectivity
corresponds to a tumour sub-network with many inter-cellular signalling edges,
enabling faster and larger cascades.  The evolution of $k(t)$ over the
simulation reveals whether the system self-organises to a critical connectivity.

