\section{Model Description and Simulation}

\subsection{Tissue Network Construction}

The tissue is represented as a Barab\'{a}si--Albert (BA) preferential-attachment
network with $N = 300$ nodes and $m = 2$ edges added per new node.  The BA
model is chosen because:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item It generates a scale-free degree distribution $P(k) \propto k^{-3}$,
        matching empirical intercellular signalling networks.
  \item Hub nodes (high-degree cells) naturally model oncogenic driver nodes
        (e.g.\ cells overexpressing EGFR, HER2, or TP53 mutant protein) that
        have disproportionate influence on their neighbourhood.
  \item New edges form preferentially to well-connected nodes, mimicking
        angiogenesis and paracrine signalling recruitment.
\end{itemize}
The resulting network has mean degree $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$ and maximum degree
$k_{\max} \approx 22$.

\subsection{Cell State Dynamics}

Each cell $i \in \{0, 1, \ldots, N-1\}$ carries:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item A \textbf{state} $s_i \in \{\textsc{Healthy}, \textsc{Cancerous},
        \textsc{Necrotic}\}$, initialised as \textsc{Healthy} for all cells.
  \item A \textbf{mutation load} $m_i \in \mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}$, initialised
        to 0 except for 3 seed cells which start at $\theta - 1 = 4$.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 1 — Mutation accumulation (slow drive):}
For every healthy cell $i$:
\begin{equation}
  m_i(t+1) = m_i(t) + \mathbf{1}\!\left[\,U_i < \mu_0 + |\eta_i(t)|\,\right],
  \qquad U_i \sim \mathcal{U}[0,1].
\end{equation}
If $m_i(t+1) \geq \theta$, cell $i$ converts to \textsc{Cancerous} and is
placed in the initial wave $W_0$.

\textbf{Step 2 — Recruitment cascade (fast relaxation):}
The cascade propagates in discrete waves:
\begin{equation}
  W_{n+1} = \left\{\, j \in \mathcal{N}(W_n) \cap \text{Healthy}
  \;:\; V_j < \rho \,\right\},
  \qquad V_j \sim \mathcal{U}[0,1],
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{N}(W_n)$ is the set of healthy neighbours of all cells in
wave $W_n$ and $\rho = 0.25$ is the recruitment probability.  The cascade
terminates when $W_{n+1} = \emptyset$.  Avalanche size $s = |W_0| + |W_1|
+ \cdots + |W_n|$.

\textbf{Step 3 — Necrosis (negligible in growth phase):}
In the growth phase, necrosis rate is set to zero to study pure invasion
dynamics.  A sensitivity analysis with $\nu > 0$ is discussed in
Section~\ref{sec:discussion}.

\subsection{Percolation Analysis}

To separately study the role of connectivity, an Erd\H{o}s--R\'{e}nyi random
graph with $n = 200$ nodes and mean degree $k$ is used.  Starting from 3
seed failed nodes, a threshold cascade propagates: a node fails if $\geq 40\%$
of its neighbours have failed.  The cascade fraction (proportion of network
ultimately invaded) is averaged over 25 independent realisations per $k$ value,
sweeping $k$ from 1 to 10.

