\section{Results and Analysis}

\subsection{Tumour Growth Dynamics}

Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(a) shows the tumour cell count over the simulation.
After a brief latent period during which mutations accumulate in the seed cells,
the tumour undergoes rapid, autocatalytic growth driven by recruitment cascades.
The growth is \emph{not} smooth --- it is composed of discrete episodic jumps,
each corresponding to an avalanche event.  By $t \approx 248$, all 300 cells
have been invaded.  This qualitatively reproduces the clinically observed
pattern of slow occult growth followed by explosive invasion.

The mutation-load distribution at the end of the simulation
(Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(b)) shows that all cells have reached the threshold
$\theta = 5$, confirming full malignant conversion.  Cells that converted
earliest carry the highest loads, reflecting the stochastic heterogeneity in
mutation timing --- a feature consistent with the ``Big Bang'' model of tumour
evolution \citep{sottoriva2015big}.

\subsection{Avalanche Statistics and Power-Law Distribution}

Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(c) displays the time series of recruitment avalanche
sizes.  The sizes are broadly distributed and highly intermittent, with the
system alternating between small local conversions and large system-spanning
cascades.  There is no characteristic cascade size --- the system behaves the
same way at all scales.

Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(d) shows the frequency--size distribution on a
log--log scale.  A power-law fit yields:
\begin{equation}
  P(s) \propto s^{-\alpha}, \qquad \alpha = 0.99, \quad R^2 = 0.72.
\end{equation}
The exponent $\alpha \approx 1.0$ is consistent with theoretical predictions
for SOC cascades on scale-free networks \citep{goh2003sandpile}, where network
hubs amplify cascade propagation and flatten the size distribution compared
to regular lattices (where $\alpha \approx 1.5$).  The $R^2 = 0.72$ reflects
the finite-size scatter inherent to a 300-node network; the linear
log--log relationship spans nearly two orders of magnitude.

The complementary cumulative distribution function (CCDF) in
Figure~\ref{fig:soc}(a) confirms the power-law heavy tail: the probability
that a cascade exceeds size $s$ decays as a power law, with large avalanches
(size $\geq 50$) occurring with probability $\sim 5\%$, far exceeding
any Gaussian or Poisson prediction.  In clinical terms, this means that
roughly 1-in-20 ``trigger events'' (new mutation, immune suppression episode)
leads to a massive, potentially lethal invasion cascade.

\subsection{Tumour Sub-Network Connectivity}

Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(e) shows the evolution of tumour sub-network
connectivity $k(t)$.  Once tumour growth initiates, connectivity rises
rapidly and stabilises at a mean value of $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$.  This
\emph{self-tuning} of connectivity --- without any external parameter adjustment
--- is the hallmark of SOC: the system spontaneously organises its internal
state to maintain the criticality conditions for ongoing cascades.

The stabilisation at $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$ is not arbitrary.  From the
percolation analysis (Section~\ref{sec:perc}), the critical connectivity
for system-spanning cascades is $k_c \approx 4$.  The tumour sub-network thus
sits just below the percolation threshold --- a state of \emph{marginal
criticality} that maximises sensitivity to perturbations while maintaining
finite-size cascades.  This is the SOC attractor.

\subsection{Degree Distribution of the Tumour Sub-Network}

Figure~\ref{fig:soc}(b) shows the degree distribution of the tumour
sub-network at the end of the simulation.  The distribution exhibits a
power-law tail, confirming that the tumour sub-network inherits the scale-free
topology of the underlying BA tissue network.  This has a profound implication:
the tumour contains \emph{hub cells} --- high-degree nodes with
disproportionately many signalling connections --- that act as super-spreaders
of recruitment signals.  Targeting these hub cells (e.g.\ with drugs that
specifically attack EGFR$^+$ or HER2$^+$ hub oncoproteins) would be far more
effective at halting cascades than targeting randomly chosen cells.

\subsection{Percolation Phase Transition}
\label{sec:perc}

Figure~\ref{fig:overview}(f) shows the cascade fraction as a function of mean
degree $k$ in the Erd\H{o}s--R\'{e}nyi percolation model.  The results reveal
a sharp phase transition:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item For $k \lesssim 3$: cascades remain localised (fraction $< 0.15$).
        Tumours in tissues with sparse intercellular connectivity are contained.
  \item For $k \approx 4$: a percolation transition occurs.  Cascades begin
        to span a significant fraction of the network.
  \item For $k \gtrsim 5$: cascades are system-spanning (fraction $> 0.70$).
        Full tumour invasion is inevitable once initiated.
\end{itemize}
This phase transition identifies $k_c \approx 4$ as the \emph{critical
connectivity} --- the network-theoretic invasion threshold.  Therapies that
reduce intercellular connectivity below $k_c$ (e.g.\ tight-junction enhancers,
cadherin modulators, anti-angiogenic drugs) would push the system into the
subcritical regime, preventing system-spanning cascades even if individual
malignant conversions still occur.

\subsection{Long-Range Correlations: Hurst Exponent}

Figure~\ref{fig:soc}(c) shows the rolling Hurst exponent of the tumour-growth
time series, computed over a sliding window of 40 steps.  The Hurst exponent
is consistently $H \approx 0.98 \gg 0.5$, indicating extreme persistence:
growth increments at one time are strongly positively correlated with
increments at all future times.  This is the temporal fingerprint of
criticality --- in a subcritical system, $H \to 0.5$ (random diffusion), while
at the critical point $H \to 1$ (persistent, scale-free dynamics).

The high $H$ is biologically meaningful: once a tumour begins growing, its
trajectory is highly predictable in direction (upward) but unpredictable in
magnitude (the episodic jumps have power-law sizes).  This matches the clinical
observation that progressive disease is common but the rate of progression is
highly variable.

