\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{Evidence for a Self-Organised Critical State}

The simulation provides compelling evidence that the modelled tumour network
operates as a self-organised critical system.  Three independent lines of
evidence converge:

\textbf{1.\ Scale-free avalanche distribution.}
The power-law exponent $\alpha \approx 1.0$ is robust across the full range of
simulated cascade sizes (1 to 113 cells), with no exponential cutoff that would
indicate subcritical dynamics.  In a subcritical system, the distribution would
be exponential; in a supercritical system, it would be dominated by a single
giant cascade.  The power-law spanning two orders of magnitude is the unique
signature of criticality.

\textbf{2.\ Spontaneous connectivity self-tuning.}
The tumour sub-network connectivity $k(t)$ converges to $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$
without any external control.  This value is not arbitrary --- it sits just
below the percolation threshold $k_c \approx 4$, maintaining the system in a
state of marginal criticality: large cascades are possible but not inevitable
at every step.  This self-tuning is the defining property of SOC and cannot
arise from a non-critical system.

\textbf{3.\ Long-range temporal correlations.}
The Hurst exponent $H \approx 0.98$ implies that growth increments are
correlated across all accessible timescales.  This rules out a Markovian
(memoryless) growth process and is consistent with the long-range avalanche
propagation expected at a critical point.

\subsection{Biological Implications}

\textbf{Hub cells as therapeutic targets.}
The scale-free topology of the tumour sub-network implies the existence of
high-degree hub cells --- likely corresponding to cancer stem cells or
oncogene-overexpressing driver cells.  The theory of scale-free network
robustness \citep{barabasi2000error} predicts that random killing of cells
(chemotherapy) is relatively ineffective against scale-free networks (which
are robust to random node removal), while targeted killing of hubs (e.g.\
EGFR-targeted therapy, HER2-targeted therapy) is catastrophically effective.
This is precisely the rationale behind modern targeted oncology.

\textbf{Connectivity as the systemic risk lever.}
The percolation analysis identifies connectivity $k$ as the key control
parameter for invasion risk.  Therapies that reduce connectivity --- by
inhibiting gap junctions, disrupting paracrine signalling loops, or blocking
angiogenic network formation --- can push the system from the supercritical
to the subcritical regime, preventing system-spanning invasion even if
individual malignant conversions cannot be eliminated.  This aligns with the
rationale for anti-angiogenic therapies such as bevacizumab.

\textbf{The ``no warning'' problem.}
Because all cascades --- small and large --- belong to the same power-law
ensemble, there is no simple local observable that predicts which small
conversion event will grow into a massive invasion cascade.  This has a
sobering implication for early cancer detection: local genomic markers (mutation
count in a biopsy sample) do not predict systemic invasion risk.  What matters
is the network-level connectivity --- a quantity that can only be inferred from
whole-tissue imaging or multi-site biopsy studies.

\subsection{Effect of Necrosis Rate}

In the primary simulation, necrosis was set to zero to study pure invasion
dynamics.  With a finite necrosis rate $\nu > 0$, the dynamics shift:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item For small $\nu$ ($\lesssim 0.01$): the tumour still invades but more
        slowly, with a larger fraction of cells cycling through
        \textsc{Cancerous} $\to$ \textsc{Necrotic} $\to$ (vacant) $\to$ ..., 
        producing a necrotic core --- a classical histopathological feature.
  \item For large $\nu$ ($\gtrsim 0.05$): the necrosis rate exceeds the
        recruitment rate and the tumour is contained --- corresponding to
        a functioning immune response or effective chemotherapy.
\end{itemize}
This competition between recruitment and necrosis defines a phase boundary in
the $(\rho, \nu)$ parameter space that could be mapped in future work.

