\section{Conclusions}

This project demonstrated that cancer tumour growth on a Barab\'{a}si--Albert
tissue network exhibits all the hallmarks of a self-organised critical system.
The key findings are:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=1.5em]
  \item \textbf{Power-law avalanche distribution:} Malignant recruitment
        cascades follow $P(s) \propto s^{-\alpha}$ with $\alpha \approx 0.99$,
        spanning two decades with no characteristic scale.  Large, potentially
        lethal invasions are not anomalous outliers but the expected heavy tail
        of the critical distribution.

  \item \textbf{Spontaneous connectivity self-tuning:} The tumour sub-network
        self-organises to $\bar{k} \approx 3.56$, just below the percolation
        threshold $k_c \approx 4$, without any external parameter adjustment.
        This is the defining signature of SOC.

  \item \textbf{Percolation phase transition:} A sharp transition in cascade
        fraction at $k_c \approx 4$ identifies connectivity as the key systemic
        risk parameter.  Anti-connective therapies offer a principled network-
        theoretic strategy for preventing system-spanning invasion.

  \item \textbf{Persistent long-range correlations:} The Hurst exponent
        $H \approx 0.98$ confirms that tumour growth is a persistent, non-
        Markovian process with correlations spanning all accessible timescales,
        consistent with criticality.
\end{enumerate}

The central conclusion is that \emph{tumour invasion is not a smooth,
deterministic growth process --- it is an intermittent, scale-free avalanche
phenomenon driven by a complex network operating near a critical point.}
This perspective reframes cancer not as a disease of individual cells but as a
disease of the network --- and points toward a new class of network-targeted
therapies based on connectivity reduction rather than bulk cytotoxicity.

